gomodel:SYNGO_4784  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 2, S2: high resolution imaging shows ANK3 (ankyrin-G) is localized to postsynapses, at both spine head and neck, in primary cultures of rat cortical neurons. Quantification of overlap between ANK3~Bassoon is similar to ANK3~PSD95 (Fig. S2G).\n\nAuthors observed; \"To confirm presence of ankyrin-G at synapses, we immunostained for ankyrin-G and either the presynaptic marker bassoon (Figure 2C) or postsynaptic scaffold PSD95 (Figure 2D); both markers exhibited substantial colocalization with ankyrin-G (Figure S2D)\"\n\nFigure 4: the 190kDa short form of ANK3 is localized to spines. \"Quantification of the fluorescence intensity of both isoforms in spines revealed 60% less spine localization of GFPAnkG270 compared with GFPAnkG190 and a reduced spine:shaft ratio (***p < 0.0002; Figures 4E and S4B), suggesting that the 190 kDa isoform is localized at synaptic sites in cortical neurons\"\n\nFigure 8: ANK3 (ankyrin-G) has greater association with both the cell membrane and cytoskeleton following a learning task in mice.. Experimental description: Supplemental M&M: \"Dissociated cultures of primary cortical neurons were prepared from E18 Sprague-Dawley rat embryos.\"\n\nantibodies:\nAnkyrin-G mAb (Neuromab)\nAnkyrin-G pAb (Santa Cruz)\nAnkyrin-G pAb (from V. Bennett)\n\n\"GFP-Ankyrin-G-190 and RFP-Ankyrin-G-270 were purchased from Addgene (#31059, #42566). RNAi constructs were purchased from Origene, in the pGFP-V-RS vector with a turboGFP element to enable identification of transfected cells. The target sequence used was GGCAGAACGAGACGCCAAGTGGAAGCCTA\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2022-08-30" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_4784" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

